occupational name for a fisherman, from <i>orfe</i>, a species of freshwater fish. Alternatively, a habitational name from Urff near Kassel, formerly Orpha."],"variants":[{"name":"Orff","meanings":["German: variant of   Orf  ."]}]},{"name":"Yorkshire","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from the county of Yorkshire."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":18,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Maud of Yorkshire was born about 1364, in Yorkshire, England. She married William de Sewerby before 1395. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died about 1401, in Sowerby, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 39."},"et":{"about 1364–about 1401":"umbes 1364–umbes 1401","1366–1433":"1366–1433","1380–1466":"1380–1466","1393–Female":"1393–Surnud","1395–1450":"1395–1450","–1454":"–1454","1364–1401":"1364–1401","about 1393":"umbes 1393","about 1380":"umbes 1380","from 9 January 1395 to 8 January 1396":"9. jaanuar 1395 kuni 8. jaanuar 1396","1450":"1450","1395":"1395","bef 1395":"enne 1395","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","1380":"1380","1401":"1401","1466":"1466","1433":"1433","1454":"1454","1366":"1366","1364":"1364","about 1401":"umbes 1401","about 1364":"umbes 1364","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Sewerby with Marton, Yorkshire, England":"Sewerby with Marton, Yorkshire, England","Sowerby, Yorkshire, England":"Sowerby, Yorkshire, England","Sewerby,Yorkshire,England":"Sewerby with Marton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1364–about 1401":"noin 1364–noin 1401","1366–1433":"1366–1433","1380–1466":"1380–1466","1393–Female":"1393–Kuollut","1395–1450":"1395–1450","–1454":"–1454","1364–1401":"1364–1401","about 1393":"noin 1393","about 1380":"noin 1380","from 9 January 1395 to 8 January 1396":"vuodesta 9. tammikuuta 1395 vuoteen 8. tammikuuta 1396","1450":"1450","1395":"1395","bef 1395":"ennen vuotta 1395","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","1380":"1380","1401":"1401","1466":"1466","1433":"1433","1454":"1454","1366":"1366","1364":"1364","about 1401":"noin 1401","about 1364":"noin 1364","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Sewerby with Marton, Yorkshire, England":"Sewerby with Marton, Yorkshire, England","Sowerby, Yorkshire, England":"Sowerby, Yorkshire, England","Sewerby,Yorkshire,England":"Sewerby with Marton, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuni